::telegram-agent::skills ns
meta {
    doc: """
    Example skills for the Team Brain Telegram agent. Demonstrates the
    three flavors of skill authoring used by the resolver:

    1. **Inline-body Hot skill** (`telegram-tone`) — the body is a
       triple-quoted string literal directly on the `meta {skill: …}`
       map. Shortest form, best for tight, agent-specific guidance.

    2. **Bundled-tool skill** (`coach-on-stats`) — same inline body,
       plus a `tools:` entry that ships a callable `lookup-recent-stats`
       tool to the model whenever the skill is read. The tool reads
       directly from `::telegram-agent::agent/brain-stats`.

    3. **Markdown-bodied skill** — see
       `resources/telegram-agent/skills/group-summary.skill.md`. The
       skill-stub codegen turns it into a generated `.skill.hot` file
       under `hot/src/_skills/telegram-agent/skills/` containing a
       prompt-only `Skill` value with the Markdown body wired in.

    To make these live for a chat-loop based command (e.g. a future
    `/coach` handler), add them to the chat options' `skills:` list:

    ```hot
    ::skill ::ai::skill
    skills ::skill/for-agent([
        telegram-tone,
        coach-on-stats,
        ::skills::telegram-agent::skills::group-summary/group-summary,
    ])
    ::chat/run-loop(messages, ChatOptions({…, skills: skills}))
    ```
    """
}

::store ::hot::store
::tool  ::ai::tool

// ============================================================================
// 1. Inline-body Hot skill
// ============================================================================

telegram-tone
meta {
    skill: {
        name: "telegram-tone",
        description: "Voice and formatting rules for Team Brain replies in Telegram chats.",
        // The `transport:telegram` tag is read by
        // `::telegram-agent::agent/skills-for-session`: skills carrying
        // a `transport:*` token are hidden from the LLM whenever the
        // active session uses a different transport. Drop the tag if
        // you want this skill always-on.
        when: ["reply to user", "format chat message", "summarize for telegram", "transport:telegram"],
        body: """
            # Telegram reply tone

            - Keep it tight: one to three short paragraphs unless the user
            asked for detail. Telegram clips long messages on mobile.
            - Use the lightweight HTML the bot already renders — `<b>`,
            `<i>`, `<code>`, and `<a href="…">…</a>`. Skip Markdown
            headers (`#`, `##`) and triple-backtick code fences; they
            render as raw text.
            - Cite teammates as `<b>${name}</b>` when summarizing what
            someone said, so the attribution stands out at a glance.
            - Never use exclamation marks except when celebrating an
            explicit user achievement (a shipped feature, a closed
            incident, etc.). The Telegram chat is a working space, not
            a marketing channel.
            - When you don't have enough memory to answer, say so plainly
            in one line and suggest what the user could ask instead.
            """,
    }
}
fn () { {} }

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Slack tone — counterpart to telegram-tone, applied when the active
// session is a Slack channel. The skill resolver picks one or the
// other based on the `transport:` cue the dispatcher passes; both
// stay registered globally so a single bot serving both transports
// can reach for whichever fits the active conversation.
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

slack-tone
meta {
    skill: {
        name: "slack-tone",
        description: "Voice and formatting rules for Team Brain replies in Slack channels.",
        // See `telegram-tone` above for how the `transport:*` tag is
        // consumed by the per-session skill resolver.
        when: ["reply to user", "format chat message", "summarize for slack", "transport:slack"],
        body: """
            # Slack reply tone

            - Use Slack's mrkdwn, NOT HTML. `*bold*`, `_italic_`,
            `` `code` ``, ```` ``` ```` for fences, `<https://example.com|label>`
            for links. HTML tags (`<b>`, `<i>`, `<a href>`) render as
            raw text and look broken.
            - Lead with one short sentence summarizing the answer, then
            optional bullets. Slack threads expect skim-ability.
            - Cite teammates as `<@USERID>` when you have the Slack id
            in metadata, otherwise plain `*name*`. Avoid `@channel` /
            `@here` — Team Brain shouldn't be paging the whole channel.
            - Never lead with greetings ("Hi everyone!") or sign-offs
            ("Hope this helps!"). Channels are noisy; every line should
            carry information.
            - When you don't have enough memory to answer, say so in
            one line and suggest a follow-up the user could try.
            """,
    }
}
fn () { {} }

// ============================================================================
// 2. Bundled-tool skill
// ============================================================================
//
// `coach-on-stats` ships a `lookup-recent-stats` tool alongside its
// instructions. When the model reads this skill via `read_skill`, the
// tool becomes callable so the LLM can ground its advice in real
// numbers (today's call count, today's token estimate, last model
// used) instead of guessing.

lookup-recent-stats
meta {
    doc: """
    Bundled tool for `coach-on-stats`. Reads today's AI-call counter,
    today's estimated token total, and the most-recent model name from
    `::telegram-agent::agent/brain-stats` for a given chat.

    Stats are keyed by `${session.id}:...` (transport-prefixed, e.g.
    `telegram:-100…` or `slack:T1:C2`). The model can pass an explicit
    `session_id` if it knows one, otherwise the tool defaults to the
    first registered session — handy for single-tenant installs and
    keeps the tool callable even when the LLM hasn't been told which
    session is active.

    Returns a `{calls, tokens, last-model}` map; missing keys default
    to zero / "(none)" so the tool always returns a populated shape
    the model can summarize.
    """,
}
fn (session-id: Str?): Map {
    day  ::telegram-agent::agent/today-bucket()
    stats ::telegram-agent::agent/brain-stats
    raw-sid or(session-id, "")
    bucket cond {
        not(is-empty(raw-sid)) => { raw-sid }
        => {
            registered ::telegram-agent::agent/list-registered-sessions()
            cond {
                is-empty(registered) => { "" }
                => { first(registered).id }
            }
        }
    }
    {
        session-id: bucket,
        calls:      or(::store/get(stats, `${bucket}:calls:${day}`), 0),
        tokens:     or(::store/get(stats, `${bucket}:tokens:${day}`), 0),
        last-model: or(::store/get(stats, `${bucket}:last-model`), "(none)"),
    }
}

// NOTE: `coach-on-stats` originally bundled `lookup-recent-stats` via
// `meta {skill: {tools: [::ai::tool/Tool({...})]}}`. That blew up at
// runtime because Hot's meta literals serialize the constructor call
// as a deferred AST node — when the skill machinery later coerces
// `Vec<::ai::tool/Tool>?` it tries to execute the AST as a lambda and
// loses the namespace alias context (the lookup falls back to a bare
// `::tool/Tool` and 404s). Until `::ai::skill/from-fn` learns to
// materialize a `tool-fns:` (Vec<Fn>) field via `::ai::tool/from-fn`,
// the workaround is to list the helper as a top-level agent tool in
// `::telegram-agent::agent/agent-tools` so it's still callable when
// the model decides to coach.
coach-on-stats
meta {
    skill: {
        name: "coach-on-stats",
        description: "Suggest next actions for a Team Brain chat based on today's usage.",
        when: ["coach the team", "review usage", "suggest next steps"],
        body: """
            # Coaching from today's usage

            When a user asks how the chat is doing, call
            `lookup_recent_stats` (no arguments needed — it defaults to
            the active session) and use the returned
            `{calls, tokens, last-model}` to ground your advice:

            - Zero `calls` so far today → suggest one or two concrete
            prompts the user can try (`/summary 6h`, `/decisions`,
            `/ask what blocked us yesterday?`).
            - High `tokens` (over ~50k) → mention they can switch to a
            smaller model with `/ai gpt-mini` for cheaper follow-ups.
            - `last-model` differs from what the user asked about → call
            that out so the user notices the active model.

            Always quote the actual numbers in your reply so the
            recommendation is auditable.
            """,
    }
}
fn () { {} }
